        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the SpaceX S-1 filing, here are the major business segments, business lines, and initiatives, along with disclosed revenue figures and operational metrics.\n\n### **1. Reportable Business Segments**\nThe company has **three reportable segments**:\n*   **Space Segment**\n*   **Connectivity Segment**\n*   **AI Segment**\n\n---\n\n### **2. Segment Details, Business Lines, and Initiatives**\n\n#### **Space Segment**\n*   **Description:** Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale.\n*   **Key Offerings/Lines:**\n    *   **Falcon 9 & Falcon Heavy Rockets:** Reusable launch vehicles for satellite, cargo, and crew missions.\n    *   **Starship:** Next-generation, fully reusable transportation system for crew, cargo, satellites, and data centers to Earth orbit, the Moon, Mars, and beyond. Over $15 billion invested.\n*   **Key Customers:** Commercial, civil, international, and government customers. The primary launch provider for the U.S. government.\n*   **Operational Metrics (as of March 31, 2026):**\n    *   Approximately 650 orbital space launches completed, with an over 99% mission success rate.\n    *   Over 540 launches completed by a flight-proven Falcon rocket.\n    *   In 2025: 170 missions completed; launched over 2,200 metric tons (representing over 80% of global mass to orbit).\n    *   Falcon 9 is the most frequently flown active orbital launch vehicle (approx. 620 launches over 15 years).\n*   **Financial Performance (2025):**\n    *   **Revenue:** Not broken out separately for the segment.\n    *   **Loss from Operations:** $(657) million.\n    *   **Segment Adjusted EBITDA:** $653 million.\n    *   **Capital Expenditure:** $3,832 million in 2025; $1,052 million for Q1 2026.\n    *   **R&D Funding Impact:** Included $3,004 million in R&D funding.\n\n#### **Connectivity Segment**\n*   **Description:** Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband data and communications network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit.\n*   **Key Offerings/Lines:**\n    *   **Starlink Consumer Broadband:** High-speed internet for residential users. Median download speed of 225 Mbps during peak hours.\n    *   **Enterprise Solutions:** High-speed, low-latency internet for enterprises across industries (construction, agriculture, aviation, maritime, etc.).\n    *   **Government Solutions:** High-speed, resilient connectivity for government customers.\n    *   **Starlink Mobile:** Global satellite-to-mobile service (texting and voice) to reduce mobile "dead zones."\n*   **Initiatives:**\n    *   **Next-Generation V3 Satellites:** Designed to offer 1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite. Deployment via Starship to begin in H2 2026.\n    *   **Constellation Expansion:** Over 23,000 inter-satellite lasers create a dynamic mesh network in space.\n*   **Operational Metrics (as of March 31, 2026):**\n    *   ~9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in LEO, accounting for ~75% of all active maneuverable satellites.\n    *   **Starlink Subscribers:** Approximately **10.3 million** across 164 countries/territories (up 105% YoY).\n    *   **Starlink Subscriber ARPU:** Strategy focused on driving sustainable revenue growth through operational efficiencies and scale, with ARPU expected to decline as international subscriber mix increases.\n    *   Serves millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers.\n*   **Financial Performance:**\n    *   **Revenue:** Not broken out separately for the segment, but Connectivity is a primary driver of near-term revenue growth.\n    *   **Segment Adjusted EBITDA:** Positive on a sustained basis beginning in 2023.\n    *   **Capital Expenditure:** $4,178 million in 2025; $1,332 million for Q1 2026.\n\n#### **AI Segment**\n*   **Description:** Operates a vertically integrated AI platform.\n*   **Key Offerings/Lines:**\n    *   **Grok:** A "truth-seeking" frontier Large Language Model (LLM).\n    *   **AI Solutions:** For consumer and enterprise customers (e.g., Grok Business, Grok Enterprise on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing).\n    *   **X:** A real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform.\n    *   **AI Computational Infrastructure:** Rapidly scaling associated compute infrastructure on Earth, with the goal of extending to space.\n*   **Initiatives:** Scaling the AI platform and compute infrastructure at an industry-leading pace and cost efficiency.\n*   **Financial Performance:**\n    *   **Revenue:** Not disclosed separately.\n    *   **Capital Expenditure:** $7,723 million for Q1 2026 (indicating massive current investment in AI infrastructure).\n\n---\n\n### **3. Consolidated Financial Highlights**\n*   **Total Revenue (Q1 2026):** **$4,694 million** on a consolidated basis.\n*   **Total Capital Expenditure (Q1 2026):** **$10,107 million** (Sum of Space: $1,052M + Connectivity: $1,332M + AI: $7,723M).\n\n### **Summary Table**\n\n| Segment | Core Business Lines | Key Operational Metrics (as of March 31, 2026) | 2025 Capital Expenditure | Q1 2026 Capital Expenditure |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Space** | Falcon 9/Heavy, Starship, Launch Services | ~650 launches, 99% success rate, 80%+ global mass to orbit (2025) | $3,832 million | $1,052 million |\n| **Connectivity** | Starlink Consumer Broadband, Enterprise Solutions, Government Solutions, Starlink Mobile | ~9,600 satellites, ~10.3 million Subscribers, 164 markets | $4,178 million | $1,332 million |\n| **AI** | Grok LLM, AI Solutions (B2B/B2C), X Platform, AI Infrastructure | Scaling compute infrastructure | Not Separately Disclosed | $7,723 million |\n\n**Note:** Specific segment-level revenue figures were not disclosed in the provided excerpts. The filings emphasize the **Connectivity** and **AI** segments as the primary drivers of near-term revenue growth, while the **Space** segment provides the foundational infrastructure and launch advantage enabling the other businesses.',
