    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Defined Terms from the SpaceX S-1 Filing Preamble\n\nBelow is a comprehensive list of all glossary and defined terms found in the provided excerpts from the S-1 filing, organized thematically.\n\n---\n\n## Core Business Segments & Corporate Terms\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"Space segment"** | Includes customer launch operations and offerings and services that utilize or support space-based infrastructure and capabilities, including launch services, satellite systems, and space-enabled technologies. |\n| **"Connectivity segment"** | Includes Starlink and associated offerings. |\n| **"SpaceX" / "Company" / "we" / "our" / "us"** | Space Exploration Technologies Corp. and its consolidated subsidiaries. |\n| **"bylaws"** | The form of amended and restated bylaws of the Company, to be effective upon completion of the offering. |\n| **"charter"** | The form of restated certificate of formation of the Company, to be effective upon completion of the offering. |\n| **"board"** | The board of directors of the Company. |\n| **"Credit Agreements"** | SpaceX Credit Facility and SpaceX Bridge Loan. |\n\n---\n\n## Starlink Products & Services\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"Starlink"** | Global Low-Earth Orbit satellite constellation and broadband network designed to deliver high-speed, low-latency internet connectivity worldwide. |\n| **"Starlink Consumer Broadband"** | A category of Starlink active users encompassing both individual residential users (households and personal use) and small-to-medium-sized businesses. |\n| **"Starlink Fixed Site"** | A category of Starlink active users encompassing exclusively enterprise customers. |\n| **"Starlink Kit"** | A set of products needed to connect to the Starlink network, typically including a Starlink antenna and related hardware. |\n| **"Starlink Mobile"** | A service that provides cellular connectivity directly to everyday smartphones via satellites, supplementing terrestrial networks and substantially reducing mobile dead zones. |\n| **"Starlink Subscriber"** | A unique Service Line directly assigned to a Starlink.com account registered to a person or entity that does not have a direct, negotiated agreement with the Starlink sales team. |\n| **"Starlink User Terminal"** | A device developed by the Company that connects to the Starlink satellite constellation to deliver high-speed, low-latency internet. |\n| **"Starshield"** | A secure satellite network designed specifically for government customers and national security applications. |\n| **"Mobile Satellite Service"** | Providing wireless voice, messaging, and data connectivity to, from, or between mobile devices by using orbiting satellites rather than terrestrial cell towers. |\n| **"mobile network operators" (MNOs)** | Local entities of companies that provide mobile phone services to customers, with whom SpaceX partners for satellite-to-mobile connectivity. May also include mobile virtual network operators. |\n\n---\n\n## Launch Vehicles & Aerospace Hardware\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"Starship"** | A fully reusable, super heavy-lift launch vehicle. Can describe the stacked vehicle (booster and upper stage) or upper stage only. Expected to commence payload delivery to orbit. |\n| **"Super Heavy"** | The reusable first-stage booster for the Starship launch vehicle, powered by 33 Raptor engines. |\n| **"Merlin"** | The Merlin family of engines, including vacuum and sea level variants, fully powering the Falcon 9 rocket. |\n| **"Raptor engines"** | High-performance family of engines developed and produced by the Company, powering the Super Heavy booster and Starship upper stage, designed for efficiency and reusability. |\n| **"booster"** | The first-stage rocket that provides the primary thrust during launch. |\n| **"booster catch"** | A recovery method in which a returning first-stage rocket booster is captured mid-air by mechanical arms on the launch tower rather than on legs at a landing zone or at sea. |\n| **"booster launch"** | A rocket launch in which a booster stage provides the primary thrust during liftoff and the initial phase of ascent before separating from the vehicle. |\n| **"propellant"** | The chemical substance or combination of substances consumed by a rocket engine to produce thrust by generating high-velocity exhaust gases. |\n| **"propulsive landing"** | The process of landing a rocket or spacecraft using its engines to control descent and touchdown. |\n| **"reflight"** | The reuse of a flight-proven rocket booster or upper stage that has successfully completed a prior space mission and has been recovered, refurbished, and certified for subsequent launches. |\n| **"return payload mass"** | The theoretical payload mass that a particular spacecraft is capable of bringing back to Earth from a specified orbit under specific conditions, derived from advanced computer simulations and performance modelling. |\n| **"crewmember"** | A person who has traveled on the Company\'s spacecraft, measured by each mission. |\n| **"mission success rate"** | The proportion of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy missions that achieve their primary objectives. Does not include Starship flight tests. |\n\n---\n\n## Orbital & Technical Terms\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"spectrum"** | The range of electromagnetic frequencies used for wireless communication, with licensed spectrum granting use for specific services. |\n| **"Sun-synchronous orbit"** | A type of polar orbit around a planet in which a satellite passes over any given point of the planet\'s surface at the same local mean solar time, allowing for consistent solar energy capture. |\n| **"Mid-Earth Orbit" (MEO)** | An orbital region between approximately 2,000 km and 35,786 km above Earth\'s surface. |\n| **"microgravity"** | Very weak gravity, such as that experienced in orbiting spacecraft, which allows for unique manufacturing processes like creating ultra-pure materials. |\n| **"downlink capacity"** | The maximum rate at which data can be transmitted from a satellite to users over a network or communication link in a given period of time. |\n| **"radiative cooling"** | A cooling method that dissipates heat by radiating it into space, often passively, and is expected to be used in orbital AI compute infrastructure. |\n\n---\n\n## AI Products & Services\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"SuperGrok"** | Subscription-based Grok service that provides users with expanded access to Grok models and related tools. |\n| **"SuperGrok Heavy"** | Subscription-based Grok service tier providing expanded access to Grok models and related tools, including higher usage limits relative to SuperGrok. |\n| **"SuperGrok Lite"** | Subscription-based Grok service tier providing basic access to Grok models. |\n| **"supported accounts"** | In the context of the X platform and Grok, a human, bot or similar account that logged into the X platform or Grok. The total number may include fake, spam, or bot accounts if they are active. |\n| **"daily posts"** | On X and Grok, the aggregate volume of original posts, replies, reposts, quotes, and media shared daily by users, and the real-time interactions, analysis, and generative capabilities provided by Grok. May include AI-generated posts. |\n\n---\n\n## AI Compute Infrastructure\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"COLOSSUS"** | Flagship data center, located on Paul R. Lowry Road in Memphis, Tennessee. |\n| **"COLOSSUS II"** | Data centers in Memphis, Tennessee and Southaven, Mississippi, part of a coherent gigawatt-scale AI training cluster. |\n| **"Terafab"** | A chip manufacturing initiative with a long-term goal of producing one terawatt of compute capacity. |\n| **"terawatt"** | One trillion watts. |\n| **"terawatt-scale"** | Infrastructure, systems, or facilities designed to generate, transmit, or consume approximately one terawatt or more of electrical power capacity. |\n| **"terrestrial AI compute"** | Artificial intelligence computing infrastructure located on Earth, such as data centers and supercomputers, used for training and running AI models. |\n| **"Power Usage Effectiveness"** | The global standard metric for data center efficiency, calculated as the ratio of total facility power to IT equipment power. |\n| **"megawatt"** | One million watts. |\n| **"Megapack"** | A containerized, utility-scale lithium-ion battery energy storage system produced by Tesla, designed to stabilize power grids, store renewable energy, and replace fossil fuel peaker plants. |\n| **"Moore\'s Law"** | An observation that the number of transistors on a microchip doubles roughly every two years, leading to exponentially faster, smaller, and cheaper electronics. |\n\n---\n\n## Debt & Financial Instruments\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"SpaceX Bridge Loan"** | The Bridge Loan Credit Agreement, dated as of March 2, 2026, among the Company (as borrower), guarantors, lenders, and Goldman Sachs Bank USA (as administrative agent and lender). |\n| **"SpaceX Credit Facility"** | The Credit Agreement, dated as of February 7, 2025, among the Company (as borrower), guarantors, lenders, and Bank of America, N.A. (as administrative agent), as amended by the First Amendment dated March 2, 2026. Was further amended in May 2026 to increase borrowing capacity and extend the maturity date. |\n\n---\n\n## Strategic & Programmatic References\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|------|-----------|\n| **"Artemis program"** | A NASA program aimed at landing humans on the Moon by the late 2020s. |\n| **"The Algorithm"** | A five-step iterative process used as guiding principles: make less dumb → delete unnecessary processes/parts → optimize → accelerate → automate. |\n| **"X.AI Holdings Corp."** | Acquired by SpaceX, effective February 2, 2026; its historical results were retrospectively recast into SpaceX\'s consolidated financial statements. |\n\n---\n\n## Forward-Looking Market Opportunities (from Business Overview)\n\nWhile not formal glossary entries, the S-1 preamble identifies these prospective business areas:\n\n- **Long-Haul Point-to-Point Terrestrial Travel** — Starship-based commercial transportation potentially reducing most international long-haul flights to under 30 minutes.\n- **Space Tourism** — Commercial human spaceflight and orbital tourism.\n- **Passenger and Cargo Transport to the Moon and Mars** — Interplanetary logistics enabled by reusable launch systems.\n- **Enterprise Solutions** — Starlink services across construction, agriculture, retail, telecom, hospitality, aviation, maritime, and land mobility.\n- **Government Solutions** — High-speed, resilient connectivity for government customers (including Starshield).',
