        output='Based on the excerpts from the SpaceX S-1 filing, here is a detailed disclosure summary regarding Starshield and Starlink government contracts, revenue recognition, backlog, and related financials.\n\n### **Starshield (National Security Platform)**\n\n#### **1. Contract & Business Nature**\n*   **Purpose:** A secure satellite network designed specifically for **government customers and national security applications**. It is built on Starlink\'s technology and infrastructure.\n*   **Core Missions:** Earth observation, global secure communications, and hosted payloads. Satellites are designed to integrate mission-specific sensors/instruments.\n*   **Key Feature:** Builds on Starlink\'s commercial encryption with **high-assurance cryptographic capabilities** tailored for military/government requirements.\n\n#### **2. Revenue Recognition**\n*   **Method:** Recognized **over time** for long-term (multi-year) contracts.\n*   **Accounting Policy:** Uses the **cost-to-cost input method**. Revenue is recorded based on costs incurred to date (materials, labor hours) relative to the total estimated cost at completion.\n*   **Significant Judgments:** This method requires **significant management judgment** to estimate:\n    *   Total costs to perform over the contract term.\n    *   Labor hours.\n    *   Allocation of shared costs for satellite production.\n    *   Satellite material costs.\n    *   Expected technological changes to satellites.\n\n#### **3. Backlog & Contract Values**\n*   **Total Company Backlog:** **$27.6 billion** as of March 31, 2026.\n*   **Deferred Revenue:** **$13.2 billion** as of March 31, 2026, of which **$1.2 billion** was recognized as revenue in Q1 2026.\n*   **Recognition Timeline:** Approximately **36%** of backlog is expected to be recognized within one year, **46%** within one to three years, and the remaining **18%** thereafter.\n*   **Primary Drivers:** Deferred revenue and backlog **primarily relate to Space agreements and Connectivity enterprise and government contracts** (which include Starshield).\n\n#### **4. Unit Economics & Sensitivity**\n*   **Direct unit economics for Starshield are not disclosed** separately. However, the cost-to-cost method ties revenue to incurred costs.\n*   **Profit Impact:** Changes in estimated total costs at completion can materially impact profit. The filing notes that **if combined gross margins for contracts using the cost-to-cost method had been 1% higher or lower in 2025, it would have increased or decreased revenue and operating income by approximately $15 million** (as per one sensitivity example).\n*   **Cost Components:** For Connectivity contracts (which include Starshield), cost estimates involve shared costs for satellite production, materials, and labor.\n\n---\n\n### **Starlink Government Contracts**\n\n#### **1. Contract & Business Nature**\n*   **Scope:** Part of the **"Enterprise & Government" revenue segment** within Connectivity. Includes services for public services, social impact, humanitarian efforts, and disaster response.\n*   **Examples:** Cited customers include **FEMA** (disaster recovery), **NOAA** (environmental monitoring), and governments of the **Philippines, Jamaica, and Ecuador** for connectivity in remote areas.\n*   **Structure:** Enterprise contracts are based on a combination of **subscriptions, data consumption, capacity, or other pricing models**.\n\n#### **2. Revenue Recognition**\n*   **Basis:** Recognized **over time** as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits.\n*   **For Services:** Revenue is recognized **ratably over the subscription term or based on actual data consumption**. Mobile connectivity agreements are generally multi-year but can be terminated by the customer.\n*   **For Hardware (Starlink Kit):** Revenue is recognized **at a point in time** (upon delivery or installation for certain enterprise customers), reported net of returns and chargebacks.\n\n#### **3. Specific Disclosures**\n*   **No material details** on backlog or contract values are provided separately for Starlink government business versus other enterprise contracts.\n*   **Retention Metric:** Since 2023, **no Starlink Enterprise customer contributing more than $750,000 of annual revenue has voluntarily discontinued service**, indicating strong retention.\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** Includes depreciation (launch, satellite, ground infrastructure), Kit costs, shipping, ground operations, employee compensation, payment processing fees, warranty, and inventory costs.\n\n### **Critical Audit Matter (CAM)**\nThe auditor highlights **revenue recognition—estimate of total cost at completion for certain contracts recognized over time** as a key area of audit focus. This directly involves Starshield and other long-term contracts using the cost-to-cost method, due to the **significant management judgment** required in estimating total costs.\n\n### **Summary Table**\n\n| Aspect | Starshield (National Security) | Starlink Government Contracts |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Primary Disclosure Focus** | Secure satellite network for U.S. national security. | Connectivity services for public sector and humanitarian use. |\n| **Contract Length** | Multi-year, long-term. | Varied; multi-year possible for mobile. |\n| **Revenue Recognition** | **Over time** (Cost-to-Cost method). | **Over time** for services; **Point-in-time** for kits. |\n| **Backlog/Deferred Rev.** | Included in total backlog ($27.6B) and deferred revenue ($13.2B). | Included in total backlog and deferred revenue. |\n| **Unit Economics** | Not separately disclosed; tied to cost estimates and progress. | Not separately disclosed. |\n| **Key Judgments** | Total cost estimates for satellite production and tech changes. | Subscription consumption and usage-based recognition. |',
